com: Who the fuck actually uses food delivery services? I just found out I can get free Grubhub delivery for a year and thought I’d try it out on some Del Taco last night. I figured if they waive the delivery fee I’d still have to pay a couple dollars “service charge” and maybe give a couple bucks tip, but that’s really not too terrible for the convenience. Then I looked it up and they wouldn’t even allow me to order Tuesday taco night priced tacos. Then I started looking around and all the prices were higher than if you order directly. I looked at some other places and all their prices were higher too. I knew these services took a percentage of the sales from the restaurant, but didn’t realize that seemingly all restaurants were moving that extra cost onto the customer now. Pic related. Del Taco I ordered and picked up myself because I’m no sucker and no Mr. Jackpots.

com: The Speyer wine bottle most likely holds wine, and was originally found in 1867, in what is now the Rhineland-Palatinate region of Germany near Speyer, one of the oldest settlements in the area. name: Anonymous
com:
So I'm renting an apartment (it's literally just a room with a sink and acloset) in chinatown and we don't have a kitchen. I already have a multi function rice cooker which can make oatmeal (breakfast) and rice (dinner) but now I want to cook chicken for my lunch as well.
I am wondering what the best appliance to cook with is.
I do NOT care about (((flavor))) or (((cost))) but what I DO care about is that it's small and easy to clean
Imagine you have to do dishes in your bathroom sink, that's the size of my sink.
Should I get a small 2 quart air fryer and just cook one chicken thigh at a time? Or is a traditional toaster oven a better idea?
Should I just boil a whole chicken in a crock pot? Or will that take up too much space and be impossible to clean.
Again, I DO NOT CARE about the quality of the chicken I literally just want to heat the internal temperature of the chicken to 165F and then clean up in a bathroom size sink.
Any advice much appreciated,
Thanks :D
last_replies:
[{'no': 18677941, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)20:44:51', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'instant pot
you can also clean it in your bathtub if ur sink is too small', 'time': 1670636691, 'resto': 18677893}, {'no': 18677945, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)20:45:38', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'Did you make the OP pic? It's neat
Speaking from experience, an air fryer is really effective and simple to clean. Dunno about your store situation where you are, but I saw a ninja air fryer at walmart for $69.99
I don't have an electric grill, but my aunt uses one whenever she does pork chops. They can double as griddles or panini makers and can hold more food than an air fryer. Pic related shows size. Only downside is that they usually max out at 300 Fahrenheit.
My final recommendation is air fryer. Alternately, you could go the minimalist route and just buy a clothing iron to do your meats. You can get one for like $20 lol.', 'filename': '234234', 'ext': '.png', 'w': 1218, 'h': 706, 'tn_w': 125, 'tn_h': 72, 'tim': 1670636738494066, 'time': 1670636738, 'md5': 'Ek8J9ULDLmDjqRYWD0jqPg==', 'fsize': 1286685, 'resto': 18677893}]

com:
I'll start with Spiced Rum like British sailors would have made back in the day:

>1 or 2 shots Jamaican Rum
Because Jamaican sugar plantations had leftover molasses so they had a lot of Rum
>Whole cloves and allspice
Because the British Empire had access to all the spice and they're small and easy to keep
>Lemon peel, few drops of juice
Because they had anti-scurvy citrus ration
>Bit of Molasses
Because sugar plantations again
>Hot water
They added water to Rum rations to discourage sailors stockpiling hard liquor then getting super drunk, heated because the Atlantic voyage was cold

Add a little butter at the end to give it a nice touch.

Kneading is for developing gluten for more chew and texture, like you'd do for bread. For cookies, first mix the fat and sugar until well combined. Then add the remaining wet ingredients (eggs, vanilla, etc). When that's homogeneous, mix in the dry ingredients until it's combined.

To answer your question: yes, you can use a hand mixer, it'll just take longer than in a stand mixer. If you WERE using a stand mixer to make cookies you would use the paddle attachment, not the dough hook.

I'm suspicious of your recipe. Post it so I can have a look at it.', 'time': 1670630811, 'resto': 18677566}, {'no': 18677627, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)19:10:09', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>18677610

It's such a joy to see the look on their faces when they take that first bite and realize just how much I love and care for them.

But lately, I've been feeling a little...off. Like something isn't quite right in my world. I've been hearing voices, seeing things that aren't there, and feeling like I'm constantly being watched. It's like I'm losing my grip on reality, one day at a time.

But despite all that, I still want to keep my family happy and well-fed. So I'm going to put on a brave face and share this recipe with you all. I hope you enjoy it as much as my family does!

Ingredients:

1 lb ground beef
1 onion, diced
1 cup breadcrumbs
1 egg, beaten
1/2 cup ketchup
1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
1 tablespoon mustard
1 teaspoon garlic powder
1 teaspoon onion powder
1/2 teaspoon salt
1/4 teaspoon black pepper
